<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Peplometus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peplometus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Peplometus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. From the latter genus it can easily be separated by the elongated abdomen (rounded in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). It differs also in the form of leg I in males having the leaf-like setae on tibia I (absent in the other genus).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Small spiders (ca. 3.0-4.0 mm length), with very flat body, covered with hard strongly sclerotised integument. Carapace almost square-shaped, pitted dorsally, its length only slightly exceeds its width. Chelicerae with two (exceptionally three) small teeth on promargin and on retromargin a saw-shaped tooth with four to five denticles. Abdomen slightly elongated, ratio of its length to width 1.3-1.5 (only in female of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. biscutellatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="species" species="biscutellatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">P. biscutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
1.2). In males, width of abdomen almost equal to width of carapace, abdomen of females wider and rather oval. Anterior margin of abdomen straight. Hard scutum covers dorsum of abdomen, venter also strongly armoured, with scuta as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, namely the narrow scutum with backwards extending 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“horns”">&quot;horns&quot;</normalizedToken>
at anterior edge, and a large trapezoid scutum in posterior half of abdomen. Males with a thinner sclerotised plate in front of epigastric furrow, its thick posterior margin forms narrow wedge-shaped bar (Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">138</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 184–188" captionStartId="F34" captionText="Figures 184 - 188. Peplometus nimba 184 male, holotype, habitus, dorsal view 185 venter of abdomen 186 first leg, retrolateral view 187 first leg, prolateral view 188 palpal organ, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures184-188" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427086" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">185</figureCitation>
). Numerous sclerotised bumps on sides of the abdominal venter (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 136–142" captionStartId="F25" captionText="Figures 136 - 142. Peplometus biscutellatus, male 136 habitus, dorsal view 137 habitus, lateral view 138 venter of abdomen 139 cheliceral dentition 140 first leg, dorsoprolateral view 141 first leg, dorsal view 142 palpal organ, ventral view (photos - specimen from Ghana, drawings - specimen from Sierra Leone)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.944.49921.figures136-142" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/427076" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">138</figureCitation>
). Legs short, in males the first pair slightly thicker, with enlarged femora and modified tibiae. In some species conspicuously thickened, usually flattened, in other species elongated (in this case the metatarsus I with a dorsal process). Tibiae I black, with ventral brush of long dense flattened setae, contrasting with other segments. Copulatory organs similar to those in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1900" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Pachyballus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pachyballus" order="Araneae" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Pachyballus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
